@node "Allgemeine_Hinweise" "Notes"

 Some special notes
 ------------------

 - Cycle-Gadgets are marked with a rotating symbol.
   By clicking the symbol, the next item will be appear.
   You also can click on the gadgets text to open a popup-menu
   to make your choice.

 - Some lists makes it possible to make your choice when doubble-click
   LMB over it (e.g. MSN-choosing).
@endnode

@node "DragonTools" "Usage"

  How to use DragonTools V2
  -------------------------
   
  Since version 1.x the program was changed in many ways.

  "DragonTools" now is only one program.
  The name "DragonTools" i use, because each part of the program is a
  subprogram.

  Start "DragonTools" by doubble-click its icon.
  In the appearing window you will see some buttons.
  Each of the buttons will start a subprogram:

  @{" Preferences           " link "DTPrefs" 0} (Program preferences)
  @{" Configure DataBox     " link "SDConfig" 0} (DataBox basic-setings)
  @{" MSN-hiding            " link "SDCLIR" 0} (MSN hiding)
  @{" Rating-counter        " link "SDMoney" 0} (Check/reset rating-counter)
  @{" Call-router           " link "SDDiversion" 0} (redirect incoming calls)

  
  If you have problems with DragonTools, have a look at
  @{" tested systems " link "testrechner" 0} in the appendix.
@endnode

@node "DTPrefs" "Preferences"

 At first you MUST define your serial driver and your MSN's and save them !

 Start the tool "Preferences". The opened window will have some symbols
 and "sheets".

 Symbols: 
 --------
   @{fg shine}Sheet of paper@{fg text}        default-settings
   @{fg shine}opened sheet@{fg text}          load last saved
   @{fg shine}disc@{fg text}                  save settings

 Sheets:
 -------

   @{" serial driver " link "deviceprefs" 0} where to find the DataBox
   @{" port-names    " link "portprefs" 0} define port-names
   @{" MSN-List      " link "msnprefs" 0} define MSN's
   @{" fonts         " link "deffonts" 0} choose font
@endnode

@node "deviceprefs" "preferences/device"

 preferences/device
 ------------------

 @{fg shine}Name and Unit.@{fg text}       Here you define the serial driver where you
                      have connected the DataBox (e.g.
                      serial.device).

 @{fg shine}search@{fg text}               try to find the DataBox at the serial-port you have defined.

 @{fg shine}baudrate@{fg text}             reads the actual speed of the DataBox when found at the
                      serial-port you defined.
                      To change the speed, klick the popup-gadget.
                      Now the DataBox will be set to the new speed.

 @{fg shine}product/firmware@{fg text}     if the DataBox is found at the defines serial-port, here
                      will be shown the actual info about
                      product/firmware.


   @{" port-Names    " link "portprefs" 0} 
   @{" MSN-List      " link "msnprefs" 0} 
   @{" fonts         " link "deffonts" 0}
@endnode

@node "portprefs" "define names for ports"

 preferences/port-names
 ----------------------

 Here you are able to define names for the different DataBox-ports.
 All program-modules are using these names (if needed).

 The port-names are not important and will NOT saved in the DataBox.
 The only reason for the names was to make the configuration more
 easy and comfortable.
 e.g. "Telephone1" for telephone one, or "modem" for the port where
 you placed your modem...

 Note: Only 14 characters are allowed for port-names !


   @{" serial driver " link "deviceprefs" 0} 
   @{" MSN-list      " link "msnprefs" 0}
   @{" fonts         " link "deffonts" 0}
@endnode

@node "msnprefs" "define MSN's"

 preferences/MSN-list
 --------------------
 
 To handle your MSN's easy, you should write them into here.
 Normally you get 3 MSN's with your ISDN.


 @{fg shine}Delete@{fg text}    Mark a MSN to remove it from the list and click here.

 @{fg shine}New MSN@{fg text}   Activates a prompt.
           Type in your MSN and hit return.
           The new MSN apperas in the list on the left.
           If this MSN is always present, it only will be marked.


   @{" serial driver " link "deviceprefs" 0} 
   @{" port-names    " link "portprefs" 0} 
   @{" fonts         " link "deffonts" 0}
@endnode

@node "deffonts" "choose font"

 preferences/fonts
 -----------------

 Sometime a problem: the programer try to format text-outputs
 and then on the user's screen all looks different.
 For that i implemented a font-requester to choose your prefered font.
 But...only "fixed-width" fonts can be used !

 The usage is the same as in the WB fonts-preferences.


   @{" serial driver " link "deviceprefs" 0}
   @{" port-names    " link "portprefs" 0} 
   @{" MSN-List      " link "msnprefs" 0}
@endnode

@node "SDCLIR" "MSN-hiding"

 If not deactivated by your telephone-company, normally the number
 of the person who is calling you will be transmitted by ISDN.
 You may identify this person by his number.
 Also your number will be transmitted to the people you want to call.

 Sometimes it can be improtant, that the people you want to call can NOT
 see your number and NOT identify you.

 For this reason is the @{fg shine}"MSN-hiding"@{fg text}.
 
 You can hide each MSN at each port.

 Choose the MSn you want to hide at the method to hide.
 
 Doubble-click it to activate/inactivate hiding.

 To upload the actual settings, store it in the DataBox by pressing
 the gadget.
@endnode

@node "SDDiversion" "Call-router"

 Each time you are not at home and you are waiting for important calls,
 you can redirect each incoming call to each telephone you want.

 You can choose between different ways:

  @{fg shine}BK2@{fg text}   redirect on second B-channel
        ------------------------------
        With ISDN you have 2 transmitting-channels and so you can use them at the
        same time.
        If you choose routing on second B-channel, an incoming call on line 1 will
        be redirect on line 2 to the number you have defined.


  @{fg shine}CFU@{fg text}   direct routing
        ---------------------
        This one uses NONE of your lines.
        Each incoming call will be redirect at your telephone-company to the
        number you have defined.


  @{fg shine}CFNR@{fg text}  direct routing by time
        ------------------------------------------------
        This one is the same as CFU, but your phone will ring 5 times before the
        incoming call will be redirected.


  @{fg shine}CFB@{fg text}   direct routing when busy (firmware 2.18 an up)
        --------------------------------------------
        All incoming calls will be redirected to the number you have defined, if the
        line was busy.


  @{fg shine}Start the tool "call-routing"@{fg text}. 
   
 The actual settings will be shown in a list.

 On the left you will see your MSN's and a ">" before the target-number.
 
 On the right you could see if the redirection is de/activated.


 @{fg shine}define target@{fg text}        Doubble-click a line and enter target-number.

 @{fg shine}redirection on/off@{fg text}   Doubble-click the line to de/activate routing

 @{fg shine}submit data@{fg text}          Click the gadget to submit the actual setting to
                      the DataBox
 
 @{fg shine}print@{fg text}                Clicking this symbol will send the actual settings
                      to your printer.
@endnode

@node "SDMoney" "rating-counter"

 The new opened window will show the rating for the DataBox complete
 and separately for each port.

 With the "@{fg shine}Null@{fg text}"-gadget you can reset each of the counters.
@endnode

@node "SDConfig" "configure DataBox"

 The subpprogram @{fg shine}"Configure DataBox"@{fg text} is the largets part
 of the DragonTools.

 With this programpart you can set the most important settings for
 your DataBox.

 When the window opened, DragonTools try to find the DataBox and will
 show the actual settings.

 Now you can modify this settings and store it in the DataBox.
 
 you can modify this:

   @{" DataBox                      " link "dcsystemdata" 0} DataBox-parameters
   @{" port1 to port3               " link "dcport13data" 0} Analog devices
   @{" port4                        " link "dcport4data" 0} Internal ISDN-Modem
   @{" collective call              " link "dccollectdata" 0} collective calls
   
 Also there is...

   @{" Symbols                      " link "dccommands" 0} Program-managing
@endnode

@node "dcsystemdata" "DataBox-parameters"

 Here you can modify basic-parameters from the DataBox:


 basic settings
 --------------

 @{fg shine}country-code@{fg text}   Type in the code for your country (e.g. 49 for germany)

 @{fg shine}first number@{fg text}   Type in your city-code number

 @{fg shine}Level@{fg text}          Choose one of this levels:

                full           City-calls, without a "0" at the beginning are allowed
                 
                national       Calls with ONE "0" at the beginning are allowed

                international  ALL calls are allowed

                Note : Settings you make here, have the the highest priority and
                       port-settings will be ignored !

 @{fg shine}rating-factor@{fg text}  Type in the factor which was multiplyed with the rating.
                               


 display-settings
 ----------------

 @{fg shine}Language@{fg text}        define display-language

 @{fg shine}MSNs@{fg text}            Which numbers should be shown ?
                 (none, only redirected or all)
                 (firmware 2.0 and up)

 @{fg shine}B-channel@{fg text}       How to show the B-channles ?
                 (not, normal or extended)?
                 (firmware 2.0 (normal), 2.5 (extended)

 @{fg shine}callerlist@{fg text}      Would you like to see a list of numbers they have
                 tryed to call you ?
                 (firmware 2.0 and up)

 @{fg shine}rating-counter@{fg text}  Would you like to see the ratings ?(firmware 2.0 and up)

 @{fg shine}incoming calls@{fg text}  Should incoming calls be identified ? (firmware 2.0 and up)


   @{" port1 to port3  " link "dcport13data" 0} 
   @{" port4           " link "dcport4data" 0} 
   @{" collective calls" link "dccollectdata" 0}
   
   @{" Symbols         " link "dccommands" 0}
@endnode

@node "dcport13data" "analog devices"
   
 Port1 to port3 of the DataBox are used by analog devices.

 Following parameters you can modify:

 @{fg shine}MSN@{fg text}             Define one of your MSN's for the port4.


 @{fg shine}level@{fg text}           Choose level for port4

                 half           No calls "to outer space" allowed
                 
                 full           Citycalls without a "0" at the beginning are allowed

                 national       Calls with ONE "0" at the beginning are allowed

                 international  All calls are allowed

 @{fg shine}rating-factor@{fg text} Define a factor which is multiplied ba the rating.


    @{"DataBox        " link "dcsystemdata" 0}   
    @{"port4          " link "dcport4data" 0}   
    @{"collective call" link "dccollectdata" 0}    
   
    @{"Symbols        " link "dccommands" 0}  
@endnode

